          "body": "The chapter closes with one of the most remarkable symbolic acts in the prophetic canon (vv. 59-64). Jeremiah commissions Seraiah — a staff officer accompanying Zedekiah's diplomatic mission to Babylon in 593 BC — to carry a scroll of these oracles to the very city they condemn, read them aloud, and then tie a stone to the scroll and throw it into the Euphrates. The enacted sign and the spoken word correspond exactly: 'just so shall Babylon sink down and not rise again because of the calamity that I am going to bring upon her' (v. 64). The Euphrates — the river that symbolized Babylonian power, whose waters fed the city's canals and supplied her agricultural wealth — becomes the site of the word's enactment. The scroll does not merely speak about Babylon's doom; it performs it in miniature, fifty years before Cyrus arrives. This is prophetic theology at its most concentrated: the word of the Lord once spoken is as certain as if already accomplished, and the sign makes the invisible certainty visible to anyone who watches a stone drag parchment to the bottom of a great river."
